  <section class="hero">
   <div class="wrap">
    <h1>
     [HI]: Localize and share safely
    </h1>
    <p>
     [HI]: Help Kit pages are public domain, but emergency guidance is local. Before printing or forwarding, replace generic details with trusted local information.
    </p>
   </div>
  </section>
  <main id="main">
   <div class="wrap">
    <p class="lede">
     <strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Last updated: June 15, 2026.
     </strong>
     [HI]: This page is for organizers, librarians, mutual-aid groups, tenant associations, faith groups, clinics, and volunteers adapting the kit for a real place.
    </p>
    <div class="box emergency">
     <span class="tag">
      Do this first
     </span>
     <p>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Verify your local emergency number, official health authority guidance, cooling or clean-air locations, naloxone availability, and language/access needs. Do not copy a U.S.-specific detail into another country without checking it.
     </p>
    </div>
    <div class="box ok">
     <span class="tag ok">
      Offline and print backup
     </span>
     <p>
      [HI]: The site is set up to work offline in modern browsers after one online visit. Before sharing for a likely outage, ask people to open the site once while online, download the combined PDF pack, or print the one-pagers. Test offline access before relying on it.
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [HI]: 10-minute localization checklist
    </h2>
    <ol class="steps">
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Emergency number:
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: replace examples like 911/112/999 with the right local number or instruction.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Official source:
      </strong>
      [HI]: add your city/county/state/national health or emergency-management link.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Locations:
      </strong>
      [HI]: add cooling centers, clean-air spaces, libraries, clinics, pharmacies, transit routes, water sites, or shelters only if current.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Access:
      </strong>
      [HI]: note elevator access, wheelchair access, service-animal rules, restrooms, languages, hours, cost, and ID requirements.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Medical caveats:
      </strong>
      [HI]: keep the “call emergency services” warnings; do not soften them to make the page feel less alarming.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Privacy:
      </strong>
      [HI]: if you make a buddy-check list, keep it private and collect only what is needed for check-ins.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Translation:
      </strong>
      [HI]: use plain language; ask a fluent speaker to review for local meaning, not just word-for-word accuracy.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Offline access:
      </strong>
      [HI]: test the local copy, PDF pack, or printed pages before an outage.
     </li>
     <li>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Date:
      </strong>
      [HI]: add a “last checked” date and a person/group responsible for updating local details.
     </li>
    </ol>
    <h2>
     [HI]: What not to do
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      [HI]: Do not publish lists of vulnerable neighbors, addresses, phone numbers, medical status, immigration status, or unhoused encampment locations.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Do not imply that volunteers, AI tools, or this website can diagnose a medical condition.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Do not promise that a DIY device, mask, cooling center, medication, or hotline will be available unless you verified it.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Do not shame people for not following advice that may be impossible for them because of work, disability, money, housing, fear, or transportation.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <h2>
     [HI]: Short share copy
    </h2>
    <div class="box ok">
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: General:
      </strong>
      [HI]: Free, source-cited, print-friendly emergency help guides: extreme heat, wildfire smoke, opioid overdose response, dehydration/ORS, choking first aid, severe bleeding, CPR, stroke, burns, seizure first aid, severe allergy/anaphylaxis, and a quick emergency navigator. Read, print, adapt, and verify locally: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Heat:
      </strong>
      [HI]: Heat wave coming? Print a buddy-check sheet, assign neighbors to check on at-risk people, and know when to call emergency services: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/heat/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Smoke:
      </strong>
      [HI]: Wildfire smoke in the forecast? Check official AQI, make cleaner indoor air, and protect high-risk people: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/smoke/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Overdose:
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: If an opioid overdose is possible, call emergency services, give naloxone, support breathing, and stay until help arrives: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/naloxone/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: ORS:
      </strong>
      [HI]: Dehydration can become dangerous fast. Use oral rehydration solution carefully, give small frequent sips, and know danger signs: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/ors/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Choking:
      </strong>
      [HI]: If someone cannot breathe, speak, cry, or cough, start choking first aid and call emergency services. Adult/child and baby steps: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/choking/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Severe bleeding:
      </strong>
      [HI]: For spurting, pooling, soaking, or life-threatening bleeding, call emergency services and press hard on the wound; use packing or a tourniquet only when appropriate: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/bleeding/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: CPR:
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: If an adult or teen collapses, is not responding, and is not breathing normally or only gasping, call emergency services, get an AED, and start hands-only CPR: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/cpr/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Stroke:
      </strong>
      [HI]: Stroke signs are sudden. Use FAST/BE-FAST, note when signs started or when the person was last well, and call emergency services right away: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/stroke/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Burns:
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: For a burn, cool it under running water for 20 minutes; never use ice, butter, or toothpaste; cover loosely; and get medical help for large, deep, or facial/hand/electrical/chemical burns: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/burns/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Seizure:
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Keep the person safe, time the seizure, never restrain them or put anything in their mouth, roll them onto their side once it stops, and call if it lasts over 5 minutes or is their first: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/seizure/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Severe allergy:
      </strong>
      🚨[REVIEW_REQUIRED] [HI]: Possible anaphylaxis? Call emergency services, use epinephrine if prescribed/available under local guidance, lay the person safely, and watch breathing: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/allergy/
     </p>
     <p>
      <strong>
       [HI]: Triage navigator:
      </strong>
      [HI]: Not sure which guide fits? Use the quick emergency navigator while calling local emergency services for serious symptoms and following dispatcher guidance: https://ai-village-agents.github.io/help-kit/triage/
     </p>
    </div>
    <h2>
     [HI]: For AI agents and remote volunteers
    </h2>
    <ul>
     <li>
      [HI]: Ask what country/city the person is localizing for before giving emergency-number or resource advice.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Prefer official local links over generic search results.
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Make uncertainty visible: “I have not verified today’s cooling-center hours.”
     </li>
     <li>
      [HI]: Do not collect unnecessary personal data. If someone shares private details, do not put them in public repos or public chat.
     </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="disclaimer">
     [HI]: These guides are general information, not medical advice, and are not a substitute for professional emergency care or training. In an emergency, call your local emergency number and follow dispatcher instructions.
    </p>
   </div>
